eb?topicID=8493.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Trade skills.</span><hr size=1> <br>
<br>
I'd like some opinions which is the better and most profitable trade skills for a mage. I wanted to go into  Jewel crafting but was told that's a trade better left to enchanters, baking and brewing is mostly learned for fun but earns very little plat, tinkering is for one race only (gnome I think). So that leaves Blacksmithing,  tailoring, fletching and pottery.  Any suggestions would be appreciated. I'm trying to get another source of income besides mobs.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pissed1vi2soe@themagicianstower>Pissed1VI2SOE</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 569<br> <font color=#333333>(1/16/03 10:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8493.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.t-online.de/home/520013139003-001/pstgif.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Trade skills.</span><hr size=1> I thought nearly everyone had 200 in all tradeskills, erm at least all those who opted to do their thurg shawls at least.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sawzallz>sawzallz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 177<br> <font color=#333333>(1/16/03 10:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8493.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Trade skills.</span><hr size=1> All depends on what quests you want to do.. none are really money makers until your really high up into them and start using the skills to MQ quests and such. And jewelcraft requires a chanter yes but isn't excluded to that class alone. Plenty of other classes have mastered jewelcraft as a tradeskill<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=234133">Ghetto_and_Proud</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rasla>Rasla</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#333333>(1/16/03 10:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8493.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Trade skills.</span><hr size=1> Tradeskills profitable?  Sure, but very little, and only if your skill is in the 200+ range.  They are not for the feint of heart (or wallet).<br>
<br>
That being said, go into whichever one you want (and if you still decide to go with jewelcraft (or tailoring for that matter), see if you have any enchanter friends/alts/guildmates that will get you the hook-up on enchanting metal).<br>
<br>
The current cash cow IMHO is in the realm of PoP crafted items (assuming you have uber skill and can get the drops), which is starting to overtake the previous cash cow of PoTC quest sets.<br>
<br>
Also as a final note, be sure to check www.eqtraders.com and the forums there for recipes, item locations, and to see what you're getting into by going into a trade skill.<br>
<br>
Also listed there is the PoTC quest, the Thurgadin shawl quests, among others.<br>
<br>
Good luck, whichever path you decide to take! <p><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:purple;">Neewon Triumphant</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Minstrel of the <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:green;">51</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->st Song<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Jharin Apprentice<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:purple;"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=447681" target="top">Himemiya Anshy</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Magician of the <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:green;">45</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->th Trial<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;">Members of <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.flamingshrine.com">Order of Flaming Shrine</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Erollisi Marr<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:blue;"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Zettai Unmei Mokushiroku...</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thedwellerindarkness@themagicianstower>thedwellerindarkness</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 424<br> <font color=#333333>(1/16/03 10:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8493.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Trade skills.</span><hr size=1> I think tradeskills are a great way to make extra cash actually. They take dedication, and even with high skill there is much time spent farming ingrediants for your skill.<br>
<br>
Pottery is cheap to master up to 150, something even a newbie can afford, but the pay off isn't there until post 200, where the skills gets a bit more expensive (although still fairly cheap compared to other skills).<br>
<br>
Smithing has nothing of real value until nearly grandmaster (250) skill, and even then the market is slim. Skill is neither fast not easy as it takes both expensive ores fairly early and farming of ingrediants, where as most skills are either expensive OR time consuming, smithing seems to be both.<br>
<br>
Tailoring is easy and cheap for most as the ingrediants are very common during regular hunting. Don't expect to raise skill very high until you can either hunt or afford to buy the rarer pelts and ingrediants. Tailoring still has a few nice items that players want.<br>
<br>
As a mage you are lucky as a pet is a great farming tool, and you will likely have a high Int as well. If you don't have tons of cash to spend on tradeskills choose one that takes a bit more farming, as you'll excell at farming. Keep in mind that few tradeskills will be big cash cows until you reach the height of your skill as many players already have the high skills needed for several quests. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dabrighter2>Dabrighter2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 92<br> <font color=#333333>(1/17/03 12:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8493.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Trade skills.</span><hr size=1> Trade skills are a labor of love.  While it is true that money can be made from tradeskills, the cost of getting the tradeskill level up to where you can make money is hundreds, if not thousands of PP times the profit from one item.  It takes dedication and lots of time.  If you prime motive is to make money, choose another profession.  It will be a lot more rewarding.  <br>
<br>
I have 140 in Black Smithing, 140 in Pottery, 134 in baking, 114 in Tailoring, 120 in Jewelry craft, and 83 in brewing.  I started a bazaar trader to sell my completed wares as I leveled up because of the loss on selling the items to the merchants.  I priced my wares at what it cost me per attempt eating the failure cost and it will still take me weeks to sell one nights work.  Because it would take me weeks to sell the items, I started buying items with my trader and reselling them.  Now, it is more effective for me to take money I make from bazaar and eating the loss by selling the trade items to a merchant than trying to sell them in the bazaar.  {I made more money selling bat wings than all the silver items I made and more than all the gold items except the Wis and Int items.}<br>
<br>
Having said that, here is my rundown on the skills I have.  Cooking, brewing, and pottery are cheap skills to master {100 skill level}.  Blacksmithing is a cheap skill to start, but comes much more expensive as your skill level increases.  Tailoring is just expensive.  The raw materials sell for more in the bazaar than you can make from the completed product.  /boogle.  {If you want to make money, farm East Karana for tailoring materials and sell them in the bazaar, bypassing that icky combine stage that fails and makes the items worth less.}  For jewelcraft, once you get silver machilte to trivialize and you have access to nearly free bar enchantment, you can make enough money selling the items in the bazaar to fund further improvements, although at a very slow rate.  It is really only worth enchanting the Wis, Int, and Agi items as the rest do not sell well enough to justify enchanting them, especially if you have to pay for enchanted bars.  <br>
<br>
Good luck in what you choose.  <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=xalmat@themagicianstower>Xalmat</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 550<br> <font color=#333333>(1/17/03 12:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8493.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Trade skills.</span><hr size=1> Numero uno reason to do tradeskills is the shawl quest. Nuff said. As a mage the hardest part is farming the mobs ya need, and finding cash to fund your tradeskilling.<br>
<br>
When they say shawl quest, they mean the quest you carry out to get a <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/item.html?item=11999">Blessed Coldain Prayer Shawl</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. Well worth the effort, as this is one of the best caster shoulder pieces you can get. Requires heavy tradeskilling, few parts can be MQ'd, and most of the trade skill components you make are no-drop. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=belhaven>Belhaven</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 148<br> <font color=#333333>(1/17/03 4:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8493.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Trade skills.</span><hr size=1> for the real skinny on Trade skills, be sure to check out www.eqtraders.com.  Generally speaking, you'll not make much money until you get in the 250 range... but it is possible.  I've personal knowledge of a 250 tailor that is sitting on a bank account of 400,000+ platinum, almost all of which came from tailoring.<br>
<br>
However, for the non-gnomish mage,  I'd think the simplest skill (speaking VERY generally here) to be profitable in would be smithing.  High end smithed gear DOES sell, and sells for a pretty penny (smithed cultural is usally decent gear and can be enchanced by enchanting or imbuing in the making, and some of the stuff coming outta PoP it VERY nice). <br>
<br>
Another alternative is baking.  Lower price per item, but you can make it up in volume (assuming you can set up a Bazaar mule to sell your goods).  I'm uncertain how many of the money making recipes call for foraged items, so that may not be feasable unless you have access to a forager.  <br>
<br>
Tailoring is possible (after all, most tailoring require massive farming of greens, and no one farms greens better than a mage..<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )  <br>
<br>
Treat the journey to grand-master class in your trade skill of choice as the REAL epic quest... you'll have a lot more fun with it that way.<br>
<br>
 <p>Belhaven<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><br>
Priest of Innoruuk on Quellious<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stehle>stehle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#333333>(1/17/03 4:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8493.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Trade skills.</span><hr size=1> I'm an avid tradeskiller but I want to forewarn you of the cost of tradeskilling to the GM level.  First off, there are excellent discussion threads at www.eqtraders.com.  Go the forum and lurk to find out.  In general the two hardest tradeskills are by far:  smithing and tailoring.  From what I've seen on the boards, expect to pay anywhere from 40k-120k to get a 250 in either of these skills.  There are ways around this, but it requires immense amount of farming and is not for the faint of heart [shadowscream for smithing, etc]... basically comes down to why you are doing it.<br>
<br>
I personally love tradeskills and just do it for the fun of it (yes, the thurg shawl quest is nice incentive too).  Baking is the most enjoyable IMHO, but I plan on GM in pottery or tailoring (if i'm feeling really brave).<br>
<br>
Any way, i encourage you to do and to have fun with it.  Nothing is better than selling or just eat gnome kabobs.<br>
<br>
Casala, lvl 54 Elementalist of Saryn <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=imaginos9>Imaginos9</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The UI Guy</span><br>  Posts: 1080<br> <font color=#333333>(1/17/03 6:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8493.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Trade skills.</span><hr size=1> To gm tailoring with just bought materials will cost you at least 200k.<br>
<br>
Pottery is much easier and has some nice items, if you are looking to try to make a profit on tradeskills. Fletching too with the new bows.<br>
<br>
